l). The placename derives from Middle Cornish <i>tre(f)</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + either an unrecorded Old Cornish personal name equivalent either to Old Breton <i>Ilian</i> or the recorded Old Cornish <i>Milian</i>, with mutation of <i>m</i> to <i>v</i>. This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland. Compare   Trovillion  ."]},{"name":"Trevillyan","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevelyn","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevalion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevelion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew Trevelyan was born about 1240, in Yarnscombe, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Nicholas Trevelyan, was 32 and his mother, Margaret Carminow, was 29. He married Felicia de Bodrugan about 1270, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"about 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1209–1275":"1209–1275","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1308–1363":"1308–1363","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","1363":"1363","1275